      "output": "At its most fundamental level, **water** is a chemical compound and one of the most abundant and essential substances on Earth. \n\nHere is a breakdown of what water is, looking at it through different lenses:\n\n### 1. The Chemical View\n* **Formula:** $H_2O$\n* **Composition:** Each molecule of water is made up of **two hydrogen atoms** bonded to **one oxygen atom**.\n* **State of Matter:** Water is famous for being the only natural substance on Earth that exists abundantly in three physical states: \n  * **Liquid** (the water we drink, rivers, oceans)\n  * **Solid** (ice, snow, glaciers)\n  * **Gas** (water vapor, steam, humidity)\n\n### 2. Physical and Chemical Properties\nWater has several unique and unusual properties that make it vital for life:\n* **The \"Universal Solvent\":** Because of its chemical structure, water can dissolve more substances (like salt, sugar, and minerals) than any other liquid. This is how our bodies transport nutrients and how oceans maintain their chemical balance.\n* **Cohesion and Adhesion:** Water molecules like to stick to each other (cohesion—which creates surface tension, allowing some insects to walk on water) and to other surfaces (adhesion—which helps water move up the roots of tall trees).\n* **High Heat Capacity:** Water can absorb and release large amounts of heat with only small changes in its own temperature. This helps regulate the climate of the entire planet and keeps human body temperatures stable.\n* **Density Anomaly:** Most substances shrink and become denser when they freeze, but water actually *expands* and becomes less dense. This is why ice floats, which prevents lakes and oceans from freezing solid from the bottom up, allowing marine life to survive the winter.\n\n### 3. The Ecological and Biological View\n* **The Essence of Life:** All known life depends on water. It makes up about 60% of the adult human body and roughly 71% of the Earth’s surface. \n* **The Water Cycle:** Water is constantly moving in a closed loop called the hydrologic cycle. It evaporates from oceans and lakes, forms clouds (condensation), falls back to Earth as rain or snow (precipitation), and flows back into bodies of water (collection). The water you drink today is the same water that dinosaurs drank millions of years ago!\n\nIn short, water"
